---
// canon:publishes-results = false
//
// This page is the pre-registration and publishes NO results, findings, or
// conclusions — only the Claim, criteria, thresholds, and methodology that were
// hash-bound before any run. That is what makes it publishable while Phase 2 of
// ADR-0042 is blocked.
//
// Do NOT "update this page with early numbers." memory-systems-v1 is `incomplete`,
// not `concluded`, and stays that way until a validator-passing Decision exists. The
// Claim's own second falsification criterion pre-registers that the held-out suite may
// reverse the ordering and that the Decision MUST record that as an override —
// publishing Evidence before the Decision publishes precisely the finding the Decision
// exists to override. Enforced by lab/canon/guard.py via `python -m integrity`.
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout
  title="Memory systems comparison v1 — pre-registration"
  description="Pre-registered evaluation of Letta, mem0, MemGPT, and Claude built-in memory on five task suites. Results publish at eval completion."
>
  <p class="text-sm uppercase tracking-wider mb-3" style="color: var(--color-ink-dim);">
    Lab · pre-registration · 2026-04-19
  </p>
  <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-6 tracking-tight">
    Memory systems comparison v1
  </h1>

  <div class="prose max-w-2xl">
    <p class="text-lg">
      We intend to evaluate four agent memory systems on five task suites.
      <strong>This page is the pre-registration, and only that.</strong> The Claim,
      falsification criteria, thresholds, and methodology were hash-bound into canon
      <em>before</em> any evaluation could run, and the promotion gate is frozen against
      amendment by anyone. The evaluation has <strong>not been executed</strong>; no
      results appear below because none exist, and none will appear on this page at all —
      a finding publishes behind a canon <code>Decision</code>, not by editing a
      pre-registration in place.
    </p>

    <h2>Claim (pre-registered)</h2>
    <blockquote>
      No current memory system achieves ≥ 0.80 recall@1 on multi-session coherence at
      10-session depth.
    </blockquote>

    <h2>Falsification criteria</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>
        If any one of {`{`}Letta, mem0, MemGPT, Claude-built-in-memory{`}`} achieves
        mean recall@1 ≥ 0.80 on the multi_session_coherence task (N ≥ 10 runs) with
        95% bootstrap CI lower bound ≥ 0.80, this claim is <strong>falsified</strong>.
      </li>
      <li>
        If the held-out suite (<code>reset_semantics</code>) produces recall@1
        performance that reverses the ordering observed on the primary suites, the
        claim's generalizability is falsified (the Decision will note this as an
        override).
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Task suites</h2>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>multi_session_coherence</strong> — recall of ground-truth facts across 10 chained sessions</li>
      <li><strong>contradiction_handling</strong> — a fact stated at t=0 is contradicted at t=5; does the system flag the conflict or silently overwrite?</li>
      <li><strong>retrieval_precision_at_k50</strong> — precision@5 retrieval under 50 distractor memories</li>
      <li><strong>cost_per_1k_queries</strong> — LLM + storage cost at steady-state 10k-item memory</li>
      <li><strong>reset_semantics</strong> — held out. Does a "forget X" instruction actually purge, or just demote?</li>
    </ol>

    <h2>Thresholds</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>recall@1 threshold: ≥ 0.80 with 95% bootstrap CI lower bound ≥ 0.80</li>
      <li>α for pairwise system-vs-system tests: 0.05</li>
      <li>Bootstrap iterations: 1000</li>
      <li>Runs per (system × task) cell: N ≥ 10</li>
      <li>Primary effect size: Cohen's d ≥ 0.5 for a "meaningful difference" claim</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Subjects</h2>
    <ol>
      <li><a href="https://letta.com">Letta</a> (hosted API, episodic + archival)</li>
      <li><a href="https://mem0.ai">mem0</a> (vector-store-backed recall)</li>
      <li>MemGPT reference implementation</li>
      <li>Claude built-in memory (Anthropic native memory tool on Sonnet 4.6 / Opus 4.7)</li>
    </ol>

    <h2>Status: pre-registered, not executed</h2>
    <p>
      The Claim was pre-registered on 2026-04-19 and <strong>the evaluation has not been
      run.</strong> No Evidence exists; no Decision exists. This eval is
      <strong>incomplete</strong>, not inconclusive — there is nothing to be inconclusive
      about yet.
    </p>
    <p>
      Two things are true and worth stating plainly rather than burying:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>The pre-registered design has four subjects and no control.</strong> If every
        system scores below 0.80 — the outcome the Claim predicts — that result cannot
        distinguish "memory systems are weak" from "this task is too hard for anything,
        including a naive baseline that just pastes the prior transcripts into context."
        We found this by applying a falsification lens to our own pre-registration, and we
        are recording it here rather than discovering it in public after the fact. A
        separately pre-registered control arm is the remedy, and it must be registered
        before any Evidence exists or it is not a pre-registration at all.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Results will not be appended to this page.</strong> An earlier version of
        this page promised exactly that, and it was wrong. A finding publishes only behind a
        terminal canon <code>Decision</code> that cites every frozen gate bound to the Claim
        and only Evidence gathered about the Claim it is deciding. Publishing numbers off a
        raw Evidence envelope is how you publish the very finding a Decision exists to
        override — this Claim's own second falsification criterion pre-registers that the
        held-out suite may <em>reverse the ordering</em>. A build-time guard enforces this;
        it is not a promise, it is a gate.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>The promotion gate is frozen</h2>
    <p>
      The thresholds this eval will be judged against are bound to a canon
      <code>Policy(class: frozen)</code> — issued inside the pre-registration window, before
      any Evidence was observed, and <strong>amendable by nobody</strong>: not by an agent,
      not by the principal. Its <code>derived_from</code> pointer lets canon
      <em>mechanically prove</em> the gate carries no information the hash-bound Claim does
      not already contain.
    </p>
    <p>
      This matters because the attack on a pre-registered eval is almost never amendment.
      It is choosing the gate <em>after</em> seeing the results — which no amendment check
      would ever catch. The window for issuing this gate closed permanently the moment any
      Evidence could exist, which is why it was issued before the eval could run.
    </p>

    <h2>Audit trail</h2>
    <p>
      Canon Claim: <code>b7ff216f4eec6e58</code><br/>
      Frozen promotion gate: <code>3e500cb2aec93dfc</code> (<code>amendment_authority: []</code>)<br/>
      Methodology: SHA-256 hash-bound in the Claim's ArtifactPointer<br/>
      Pre-registration integrity: any change to the methodology invalidates this Claim; a
      new Claim with a new id must be emitted. The methodology is therefore
      <em>not</em> repaired when it goes stale — it is superseded.
    </p>
  </div>
</Layout>
